fields.name: Vinyasa Flow
fields.description: Vinyasa is one of the most popular and accessible types of yoga. In this Vinyasa Flow course, you will learn some of the fundamental poses and movements, and learn how to control and utilize your breath while changing postures.
fields.tagline: A style of yoga where movement is linked to breath

fields.name: Ashtanga Primary Series
fields.description: The Ashtanga Primary Series, known as yoga therapy, is one of the most beloved yoga practices. It helps to cleanse both mind and body, while also being a fantastic form of exercise.
fields.tagline: Energetic, and dynamic movements in sequence

fields.name: Restorative Yoga
fields.description: Restorative Yoga focuses primarily on passive healing. Our Restorative Yoga practices induce deep relaxation by way of deep breathing, longer poses, and an emphasis on accepting our limitations, both physical and mental.
fields.tagline: Gentle poses for relaxation and healing

fields.name: Advanced Ashtanga
fields.description: The Ashtanga: Advanced Series, known as Sthira Bhaga, is the final sequence of Ashtanga. These classes focus on both physical strength, flexibility, and balance, to bring awareness of the movement and flow of your body.
fields.tagline: Energetic, and dynamic movements in sequence

fields.name: Advanced Vinyasa
fields.description: In these classes, you will learn advanced poses, movements, and sequences which will challenge your flexibility, breath, and strength. It's an excellent way to build endurance and lower stress.
fields.tagline: A style of yoga where movement is linked to breath

fields.name: Outdoor Yoga
fields.description: Outdoor Yoga classes are suited for all levels.  Yoga by the beach is a wonderful experience and the perfect place to connect with nature and take sun salutations.

fields.name: Introduction to Yoga
fields.description: If you've never tried yoga before, our introduction class is a great place to start. You'll learn the basic principles of practicing yoga,  and feel the benefits of breath movement.

fields.title: Your First Yoga Class
fields.content:
The first yoga class you attend can be a daunting experience. You may have some prenotions about yoga; it's only for flexible and fit people, it's all about stretching, and you'll be 'bad at it. I'm here to tell you that these ideas couldn't be further from the truth. 

Yoga in its purest form is about welcoming and accepting everybody to help them become happier and healthier. 

There are many different yoga forms, so choosing classes based on your own experience level and desired difficulty levels is totally possible. 

Yoga doesn't require anybody to be flexible, strong, and fit. By regularly practicing yoga, you'll become more flexible and stronger. These aren't necessary to begin practicing yoga but are byproducts of regular practice. 

In its essence, yoga is about acceptance; accepting yourself, your body, and your limitations. It's totally fine if you can hold certain poses or touch your toes. That doesn't mean you can't do yoga, or that you're bad at yoga. Practice and time will be the key to holding postures. Teachers and students alike completely understand that we all started in the same place; a curiosity for yoga. 

At Savasana Yoga, we have many classes for beginners and experienced yogis. We're always happy to welcome new people and help others to become happier, healthier, and stronger.
fields.snippet: The first yoga class you attend can be an overwhelming experience, but we're here to reassure you be dispeling some common misconceptions.
